{
    "analysis": "We previously loaded the four telemetry CSVs and produced concise summaries: metric, trace, and log telemetry are available and include many services; error_logs.csv had no entries. The summary shows candidate services (including ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-travel-service, etc.) and the most frequent metric KPIs (cpu, mem, socket, diskio, latency-50/90, workload, error). Next, per the prescribed workflow, we must preprocess metrics for only the allowed root-cause candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service): compute global thresholds (P95) for each component-KPI across the full series (before filtering), then filter metric data to the incident window and detect anomalies against those thresholds. This will narrow candidate faulty components and KPIs for subsequent trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and parse timestamp to UTC datetimes (use pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True)). Focus ONLY on these candidate components: [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"]. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present for these components: 1) compute the global P95 using the full available series for that (cmdb_id,kpi_name) (do NOT filter by incident window for this step); 2) then filter metric rows to the incident window from 2024-01-25 18:15:58 UTC to 2024-01-25 18:45:58 UTC (inclusive) and compute: total_points (full series count), p95 (from step 1), points_in_window (count), anomalies_in_window (count of rows in window with value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_ts_utc (UTC datetime of earliest anomaly in window or NaN if none), and max_value_in_window. Return a compact table with one row per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) containing these fields, sorted by anomalies_in_window descending, then by max_value_in_window descending. Limit the output to top 20 rows. Do not print full raw time series." }

{
    "analysis": "From metric analysis we identified memory spikes across multiple candidate services (ts-travel-service, ts-route-service, ts-order-service, ts-train-service, ts-auth-service). The largest spike is ts-travel-service.memory (earliest anomaly 2024-01-25T18:34:00Z) and other services show memory anomalies as well. Multiple services having memory faults means we must use traces to identify which faulty service is the most downstream faulty service in the call chain (root cause). Per the workflow, next is trace analysis: compute global thresholds for trace features, detect anomalies in the incident window, and summarize which candidate service’s trace features show the earliest/most severe anomalies so we can pick the downstream faulty service.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and parse timestamp to UTC datetimes (pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True)). Focus only on trace_name rows that mention any of these candidate services: [\"ts-travel-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-auth-service\"] (match when the trace_name contains that substring). For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) among these rows: 1) compute the global P95 using the full available series for that (cmdb_id,trace_name) (do NOT filter by incident window); 2) then filter the trace rows to the incident window 2024-01-25 18:15:58 UTC — 2024-01-25 18:45:58 UTC (inclusive) and compute: total_points (full series count), p95 (from step 1), points_in_window (count), anomalies_in_window (count of rows in window with value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_ts_utc (UTC datetime of earliest anomaly in window or NaN), and max_value_in_window. Also, for convenience, extract a target_service label from trace_name (e.g., if trace_name contains 'to_ts-travel-service' or 'from_ts-travel-service' set target_service='ts-travel-service'). Return two compact outputs (text/tables only):\nA) A table with one row per (cmdb_id,trace_name) containing [target_service, cmdb_id, trace_name, total_points, p95, points_in_window, anomalies_in_window, earliest_anomaly_ts_utc, max_value_in_window], sorted by anomalies_in_window desc then max_value_in_window desc, limited to top 20 rows.\nB) A per-target_service summary table listing [target_service, total_trace_anomalies (sum of anomalies_in_window across its trace_name entries), earliest_anomaly_ts_utc_across_features, most_affected_trace_name (the trace_name with highest max_value_in_window and its max_value_in_window)].\nKeep outputs compact and limit rows as requested; do not print full raw time series." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis shows the trace features for the candidate services are all zero-valued with P95=0.0, so trace telemetry does not indicate elevated error rates or latencies during the window (the statistical 'anomalies' are artefacts of zero-valued series). Metric analysis earlier highlighted memory spikes across multiple services, with ts-travel-service.memory showing the largest peak (max ~1.07e+09) and earliest anomaly at 2024-01-25T18:34:00Z — other services (ts-route, ts-order, ts-train, ts-auth) also show memory anomalies but with lower peaks and different earliest times. Since multiple services show memory faults, traces didn't help localize (they're zeroed), so next we must use logs to determine the failure reason (e.g., memory OOM, socket errors, or other). We should compute global thresholds for log KPIs (per component-log_name) using the full series, then inspect the incident window for anomalies and review actual error log messages (error_logs.csv) if present. This will help decide whether the root cause is memory usage (e.g., OOM), socket errors, or something else.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv and error_logs.csv, parse timestamps to UTC datetimes (pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True)). For log.csv: focus ONLY on these candidate services: [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"]. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) present for these services: 1) compute global P95 using the full series (do NOT filter by incident window); 2) then filter to the incident window 2024-01-25 18:15:58 UTC — 2024-01-25 18:45:58 UTC (inclusive) and compute: total_points (full series count), p95 (from step 1), points_in_window (count), anomalies_in_window (count of rows in window with value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_ts_utc (UTC datetime of earliest anomaly in window or NaN), and max_value_in_window. Return a compact table with one row per (cmdb_id, log_name) containing these fields, sorted by anomalies_in_window desc then max_value_in_window desc, limited to top 20 rows. Additionally, for error_logs.csv: report total row count overall, count of rows in the incident window, and if any rows exist in-window return up to 10 sample messages with their timestamps (UTC). Keep outputs concise and bounded (no raw full time series)." }

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metrics, traces, and logs for the five candidate services. Metric analysis showed multiple services with memory KPI breaches vs their global P95, with the largest memory peak observed on ts-travel-service (max ~1.07e+09, p95 ~8.57e+08) and its earliest memory anomaly at 2024-01-25T18:34:00Z. Trace features were zero-valued (P95=0) and provided no useful error/latency signal. Log analysis revealed spikes in log.row_count (traffic) for several services; the most pronounced traffic spike was for ts-travel-service with earliest row_count anomaly at 2024-01-25T18:22:00Z. error_logs.csv contains no error messages. Putting these together: traffic increases (log.row_count spikes around 18:22) preceded memory spikes (ts-travel-service memory spike at 18:34), and ts-travel-service shows the largest memory deviation relative to its historical P95. Traces do not help localize because the trace features are zero-valued.",
    "completed": "True",
    "instruction": "Diagnosis summary:\n- Root-cause component: ts-travel-service (service-level).\n- Failure reason: high memory usage (memory spike / memory pressure) likely induced by a sudden traffic spike. Evidence: ts-travel-service has the largest memory peak in the incident window (max ~1.07e+09 > global P95 ~8.57e+08) with earliest memory anomaly at 2024-01-25T18:34:00Z; log.row_count for ts-travel-service shows an earlier traffic spike at 2024-01-25T18:22:00Z. Traces show no elevated error/latency signals and error_logs are empty, supporting a resource (memory) overload rather than network or socket failure.\n- Suggested next actions: inspect ts-travel-service process for OOM events, heap/GC behavior, and application-level memory growth; check recent deployment/configuration changes; consider rate-limiting or autoscaling to mitigate spikes; collect full GC and heap dumps around 18:30–18:36 for root-cause confirmation." }

